{"title_page": "Mildred Stapley Byne", "text_new": "{{short description|American art historian}}\n'''Mildred Stapley Byne''' (1875-1941) was an American art historian who specialized in Spanish art and architecture. With her husband Arthur Byne (1883-1935), who she married in 1910,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eTeEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT413&dq=mildred+stapley+byne&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiinoejhPrlAhUnrVkKHb93DUU4ChDoATAFegQIBRAC#v=onepage&q=mildred%20stapley%20byne&f=false|title=The Spanish Craze: America's Fascination with the Hispanic World, 1779-1939|last=Kagan|first=Richard L.|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|year=2019|isbn=978-1-4962-1113-2|location=|pages=no page numbers given, information appears between Fig. 30 and Fig. 31|language=en}}</ref> she wrote many of the first academic works in English on the architecture and [[ironwork]] of [[Spanish colonization of the Americas|Spanish colonial North America.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://research.frick.org/directory/detail/1519|title=Byne, Mildred Stapley, 1875-1941|last=|first=|date=|website=Archives Directory for the History of Collecting, The Frick Collection|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>\n\nByne's first noted essay on \"The Great [[Isabella I of Castile|Queen Isabel]]\" was published in ''Harper's Monthly Magazine'' in June 1912.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://harpers.org/archive/1912/06/the-great-queen-isabella/|title=The great Queen Isabella|last=Byne|first=Mildred Stapley|date=June 1912|work=Harper's Magazine|access-date=2019-11-21|issn=0017-789X}}</ref> Her most famous book is ''Christopher Columbus,'' a popular biography that brought new research done in Spanish to English-speaking audiences.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a35HAAAAIAAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&dq=inauthor:%22Mildred%20Stapley%20Byne%22&pg=PR3#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Christopher Columbus|last=Byne (Mrs)|first=Mildred (Stapley)|date=1915|language=en}}</ref> Seventeen editions have been published between 1915 and 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n81070505/|title=Byne, Mildred Stapley 1875-1941|last=|first=|date=|website=OCLC WorldCat Identities|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBoth members of the couple were corresponding members of the [[Hispanic Society of America]],<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gGZJAQAAIAAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&dq=mildred%20stapley%20byne&pg=PA92#v=onepage&q=mildred%20stapley%20byne&f=false|title=Spanish Interiors and Furniture|last=Byne|first=Mildred Stapley|date=1922|publisher=W. Helburn|language=en}}</ref> and served as curators of architecture and applied arts from 1916 to 1921.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1921, the Bynes ended their relationship with the HSA and settled permanently in Madrid.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThrough their friend [[Julia Morgan]], the couple helped American collector [[William Randolph Hearst]] acquire Spanish art and decorative items.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nwWH3KSt7s4C&pg=PA219&dq=mildred+stapley+byne&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiotomrhPrlAhUip1kKHTimAS44FBDoATACegQIBBAC#v=onepage&q=mildred%20stapley%20byne&f=false|title=Moving Rooms|last=Harris|first=John|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2007|isbn=978-0-300-12420-0|location=New Haven, CT|pages=220|language=en}}</ref> After 1921, the Bynes established themselves as dealers.<ref name=\":0\" /> They also served as historical consultants for Spanish colonial and colonial-style houses in California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pcad.lib.washington.edu/person/7155/|title=PCAD - Mildred Stapley Byne|website=pcad.lib.washington.edu|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>\n\nTheir work was widely praised, and one reviewer wrote of one of their books: \"A book like this is a stimulant to the creative faculty.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_eA1AQAAMAAJ&lpg=PR5&ots=o8uJVlxBQx&dq=mildred%20stapley%20byrne&pg=PR5#v=onepage&q=mildred%20stapley%20byrne&f=false|title=The Dial|last=Bragdon|first=Claude|publisher=Jansen, McClurg & Company|year=1917|isbn=|location=London|pages=17\u201318|language=en|chapter=The Renaissance in Spain}}</ref>\n\nIn 1931, couple bought a home in Madrid built in 1885 by Don Manuel Caldero, the Marqu\u00e9s de Salamanca.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/documents/organization/66242.pdf|title=The Secretary of State's Register of Culturally Significant Property|last=|first=|publisher=Overseas Buildings Operations, Cultural Resources Committee|year=2009|isbn=|location=Arlington, VA|pages=no page numbers|chapter=Byne House, Madrid, Spain}}</ref> It was purchased by the United States government in 1944 and now serves as an American diplomatic building.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomatinspain.com/en/2017/03/the-artistic-treasures-of-the-residence-of-us-embassys-number-two/|title=The artistic treasures of the residence of US Embassy's \u2018number two\u2019|date=2017-03-21|website=The Diplomat in Spain|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> In 2006, the building was added to the [[Register of Culturally Significant Property]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe couple's last name is often misspelled as \"Byrne\" or \"Bryne.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Publications ==\n* \"The City of Towers,\" ''Harper's Monthly Magazine,'' October 1911.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://harpers.org/archive/1911/10/the-city-of-towers/|title=The city of towers|last=Byne|first=Mildred Stapley|date=October 1911|work=Harper's Magazine|access-date=2019-11-21|issn=0017-789X}}</ref>\n* \"The Great Queen Isabella,\" ''Harper's Monthly Magazine,'' June 1912.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* ''Rejer\u00eda of the Spanish Renaissance'' (New York: The Hispanic Society of America, 1914), with Arthur Byne<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/102216863|title=Rejer\u00eda of the Spanish renaissance: a collection of photographs and measured drawings with descriptive text|last=Byne|first=Arthur|last2=Byne|first2=Mildred Stapley|last3=Hispanic Society of America.|date=1914|publisher=Hispanic Society of America|series=Hispanic society publications ;no. 87|location=New York}}</ref>\n* ''Spanish Ironwork'' (New York: The Hispanic Society of America, 1915), with Arthur Byne<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/spanishironwork00byne|quote=mildred stapley byne.|title=Spanish Ironwork|last=Byne|first=Arthur|last2=Byne|first2=Mildred Stapley|last3=Stapley|first3=Mildred|date=1915|publisher=Hispanic society of America|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/spanishironwork00goog|title=Spanish Ironwork|last=Byne|first=Arthur|last2=Byne|first2=Mildred Stapley|date=1915|publisher=The Hispanic society of America|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Christopher Columbus'' (New York: The MacMillan Company, 1915)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''Spanish Architecture of the 16th Century'' (New York: G. P. Putnam and Sons, 1917), with Arthur Byne<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Translation of Orestes Ferrera, ''Causes and pretexts of the world war: a searching examination into the play and counterplay of European politics from the Franco-Prussian war to the outburst of the great world war'' (New York: American-Neo-Latin Library, 1918)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/005875687|title=Causes and pretexts of the world war; a searching examination into the play and counterplay of European politics from the Franco-Prussian war to the outburst of the great world war|last=Ferrara|first=Orestes|last2=Byne|first2=Mildred Stapley|date=1918|publisher=American-neo-Latin library|location=New York, N. Y.}}</ref>\n* ''Spanish Interiors and Furniture: Photographs and Drawings,'' vol. 1 (New York: Architectural Book Pub. Co., c. 1921-1922)\n* ''Decorated Wooden Ceilings in Spain'' (New York: G. P. Putnam and Sons, 1920), with Arthur Byne<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dLBUAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA640&ots=C71NxshuDb&dq=mildred%20stapley%20byrne&pg=PA640#v=onepage&q=mildred%20stapley%20byrne&f=false|title=The Bookseller, Newsdealer and Stationer|last=|first=|date=1920|publisher=Excelsior Publishing House|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=640|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Spanish Interiors and Furniture,'' vol. 2 (New York: William Helburn, Inc., 1922), with Arthur Byne<ref name=\":3\" />\n* ''Popular Weaving and Embroidery in Spain'' (New York: William Helburn, Inc., 1924)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n-pLAAAAMAAJ&q=Byne+weaving+embroidery&dq=Byne+weaving+embroidery&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx-PbLh_rlAhUo2FkKHXEhCs4Q6AEwAHoECAAQAg|title=Popular Weaving and Embroidery in Spain|last=Byne|first=Mildred Stapley|date=1924|publisher=W. Helburn|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Provincial Houses in Spain'' (New York: W. Helburn Inc., 1925), with Arthur Byne\n* ''Forgotten Shrines of Spain'' (New York(?): J. B. Lippincott and Co., 1926)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/forgottenshrines0000byne|url-access=registration|quote=mildred stapley byne.|title=Forgotten Shrines of Spain|last=Byne|first=Mrs Mildred (Stapley)|date=1926|publisher=J. B. Lippincott Company|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Important mediaeval and early Renaissance works of art from Spain: sculptures, furniture, textiles, tapestries, and rugs: collection of Conde de las Almenas, Madrid, Spain'' (New York : American Art Association, 1927), with Arthur Byne and Ercole Canessa.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/importantmediaev00amer|title=Important Mediaeval and early Renaissance works of art from Spain : sculptures, furniture, textiles, tapestries and rugs, collection of Conde de las Almenas, Madrid, Spain|last=|first=|publisher=American Art Association|others=|year=1927|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref>\n* ''The Sculptured Capital in Spain: a Series of Examples Dating from the Sixth to the Sixteenth Century'' (New York: William Helburn, Inc., 1928)\n* ''Spanish Gardens and Patios'' (New York(?): J. B. Lippincott and Co., 1928)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MCwhAQAAIAAJ&dq=mildred+stapley+byne&source=gbs_book_similarbooks|title=Spanish Gardens and Patios|date=1928|publisher=J. B. Lippincott Company|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Majorcan Houses and Gardens: A Spanish Island in the Mediterranean'' (New York: William Helburn, Inc., 1928), with Arthur Byne<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YVlfHQAACAAJ&dq=mildred+stapley+byne&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiinoejhPrlAhUnrVkKHb93DUU4ChDoATADegQIABAB|title=Majorcan Houses and Gardens: A Spanish Island in the Mediterranean|last=Byne|first=Arthur|last2=Byne|first2=Mildred Stapley|date=1928|publisher=W. Helbvrn Incorporated|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Other Resources ==\n* The University of Pennsylvania has compiled a [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/webbin/book/lookupname?key=Byne,+Mildred+Stapley,+1875-1941 webpage dedicated to Stapley Byne's digitized works.]\n* The couple was the subject of an unpublished thesis by Victoria Rodriguez Thiessen, ''Byne and Stapley: Scholars, Dealers, and Collectors of Spanish Decorative Arts'' (Thesis (M.A.)--Cooper-Hewitt Museum and Parsons School of Design, 1998). [https://siris-libraries.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=liball&source=~!silibraries&uri=full=3100001~!592104~!0#focus Online catalogue record.]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Byne, Mildred Stapley}}\n[[Category:American art historians]]\n[[Category:Women art historians]]\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American art historian}}\n'''Mildred Stapley Byne''' (1875-1941) was an American art historian who specialized in Spanish art and architecture. With her husband Arthur Byne (1883-1935), who she married in 1910,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eTeEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT413&dq=mildred+stapley+byne&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiinoejhPrlAhUnrVkKHb93DUU4ChDoATAFegQIBRAC#v=onepage&q=mildred%20stapley%20byne&f=false|title=The Spanish Craze: America's Fascination with the Hispanic World, 1779-1939|last=Kagan|first=Richard L.|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|year=2019|isbn=978-1-4962-1113-2|location=|pages=no page numbers given, information appears between Fig. 30 and Fig. 31|language=en}}</ref> she wrote many of the first academic works in English on the architecture and [[ironwork]] of [[Spanish colonization of the Americas|Spanish colonial North America.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://research.frick.org/directory/detail/1519|title=Byne, Mildred Stapley, 1875-1941|last=|first=|date=|website=Archives Directory for the History of Collecting, The Frick Collection|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>\n\nByne's first noted essay on \"The Great [[Isabella I of Castile|Queen Isabel]]\" was published in ''Harper's Monthly Magazine'' in June 1912.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://harpers.org/archive/1912/06/the-great-queen-isabella/|title=The great Queen Isabella|last=Byne|first=Mildred Stapley|date=June 1912|work=Harper's Magazine|access-date=2019-11-21|issn=0017-789X}}</ref> Her most famous book is ''Christopher Columbus,'' a popular biography that brought new research done in Spanish to English-speaking audiences.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a35HAAAAIAAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&dq=inauthor:%22Mildred%20Stapley%20Byne%22&pg=PR3#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Christopher Columbus|last=Byne (Mrs)|first=Mildred (Stapley)|date=1915|language=en}}</ref> Seventeen editions have been published between 1915 and 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n81070505/|title=Byne, Mildred Stapley 1875-1941|last=|first=|date=|website=OCLC WorldCat Identities|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBoth members of the couple were corresponding members of the [[Hispanic Society of America]],<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gGZJAQAAIAAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&dq=mildred%20stapley%20byne&pg=PA92#v=onepage&q=mildred%20stapley%20byne&f=false|title=Spanish Interiors and Furniture|last=Byne|first=Mildred Stapley|date=1922|publisher=W. Helburn|language=en}}</ref> and served as curators of architecture and applied arts from 1916 to 1921.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1921, the Bynes ended their relationship with the HSA and settled permanently in Madrid.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThrough their friend [[Julia Morgan]], the couple helped American collector [[William Randolph Hearst]] acquire Spanish art and decorative items.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nwWH3KSt7s4C&pg=PA219&dq=mildred+stapley+byne&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiotomrhPrlAhUip1kKHTimAS44FBDoATACegQIBBAC#v=onepage&q=mildred%20stapley%20byne&f=false|title=Moving Rooms|last=Harris|first=John|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2007|isbn=978-0-300-12420-0|location=New Haven, CT|pages=220|language=en}}</ref> After 1921, the Bynes established themselves as dealers.<ref name=\":0\" /> They also served as historical consultants for Spanish colonial and colonial-style houses in California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pcad.lib.washington.edu/person/7155/|title=PCAD - Mildred Stapley Byne|website=pcad.lib.washington.edu|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>\n\nTheir work was widely praised, and one reviewer wrote of one of their books: \"A book like this is a stimulant to the creative faculty.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_eA1AQAAMAAJ&lpg=PR5&ots=o8uJVlxBQx&dq=mildred%20stapley%20byrne&pg=PR5#v=onepage&q=mildred%20stapley%20byrne&f=false|title=The Dial|last=Bragdon|first=Claude|publisher=Jansen, McClurg & Company|year=1917|isbn=|location=London|pages=17\u201318|language=en|chapter=The Renaissance in Spain}}</ref>\n\nIn 1931, couple bought a home in Madrid built in 1885 by Don Manuel Caldero, the Marqu\u00e9s de Salamanca.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/documents/organization/66242.pdf|title=The Secretary of State's Register of Culturally Significant Property|last=|first=|publisher=Overseas Buildings Operations, Cultural Resources Committee|year=2009|isbn=|location=Arlington, VA|pages=no page numbers|chapter=Byne House, Madrid, Spain}}</ref> It was purchased by the United States government in 1944 and now serves as an American diplomatic building.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomatinspain.com/en/2017/03/the-artistic-treasures-of-the-residence-of-us-embassys-number-two/|title=The artistic treasures of the residence of US Embassy's \u2018number two\u2019|date=2017-03-21|website=The Diplomat in Spain|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> In 2006, the building was added to the [[Register of Culturally Significant Property]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe couple's last name is often misspelled as \"Byrne\" or \"Bryne.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Publications ==\n* \"The City of Towers,\" ''Harper's Monthly Magazine,'' October 1911.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://harpers.org/archive/1911/10/the-city-of-towers/|title=The city of towers|last=Byne|first=Mildred Stapley|date=October 1911|work=Harper's Magazine|access-date=2019-11-21|issn=0017-789X}}</ref>\n* \"The Great Queen Isabella,\" ''Harper's Monthly Magazine,'' June 1912.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* ''Rejer\u00eda of the Spanish Renaissance'' (New York: The Hispanic Society of America, 1914), with Arthur Byne<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/102216863|title=Rejer\u00eda of the Spanish renaissance: a collection of photographs and measured drawings with descriptive text|last=Byne|first=Arthur|last2=Byne|first2=Mildred Stapley|last3=Hispanic Society of America.|date=1914|publisher=Hispanic Society of America|series=Hispanic society publications ;no. 87|location=New York}}</ref>\n* ''Spanish Ironwork'' (New York: The Hispanic Society of America, 1915), with Arthur Byne<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/spanishironwork00byne|quote=mildred stapley byne.|title=Spanish Ironwork|last=Byne|first=Arthur|last2=Byne|first2=Mildred Stapley|last3=Stapley|first3=Mildred|date=1915|publisher=Hispanic society of America|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/spanishironwork00goog|title=Spanish Ironwork|last=Byne|first=Arthur|last2=Byne|first2=Mildred Stapley|date=1915|publisher=The Hispanic society of America|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Christopher Columbus'' (New York: The MacMillan Company, 1915)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''Spanish Architecture of the 16th Century'' (New York: G. P. Putnam and Sons, 1917), with Arthur Byne<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Translation of Orestes Ferrera, ''Causes and pretexts of the world war: a searching examination into the play and counterplay of European politics from the Franco-Prussian war to the outburst of the great world war'' (New York: American-Neo-Latin Library, 1918)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/005875687|title=Causes and pretexts of the world war; a searching examination into the play and counterplay of European politics from the Franco-Prussian war to the outburst of the great world war|last=Ferrara|first=Orestes|last2=Byne|first2=Mildred Stapley|date=1918|publisher=American-neo-Latin library|location=New York, N. Y.}}</ref>\n* ''Spanish Interiors and Furniture: Photographs and Drawings,'' vol. 1 (New York: Architectural Book Pub. Co., c. 1921-1922)\n* ''Decorated Wooden Ceilings in Spain'' (New York: G. P. Putnam and Sons, 1920), with Arthur Byne<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dLBUAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA640&ots=C71NxshuDb&dq=mildred%20stapley%20byrne&pg=PA640#v=onepage&q=mildred%20stapley%20byrne&f=false|title=The Bookseller, Newsdealer and Stationer|last=|first=|date=1920|publisher=Excelsior Publishing House|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=640|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Spanish Interiors and Furniture,'' vol. 2 (New York: William Helburn, Inc., 1922), with Arthur Byne<ref name=\":3\" />\n* ''Popular Weaving and Embroidery in Spain'' (New York: William Helburn, Inc., 1924)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n-pLAAAAMAAJ&q=Byne+weaving+embroidery&dq=Byne+weaving+embroidery&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx-PbLh_rlAhUo2FkKHXEhCs4Q6AEwAHoECAAQAg|title=Popular Weaving and Embroidery in Spain|last=Byne|first=Mildred Stapley|date=1924|publisher=W. Helburn|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Provincial Houses in Spain'' (New York: W. Helburn Inc., 1925), with Arthur Byne\n* ''Forgotten Shrines of Spain'' (New York(?): J. B. Lippincott and Co., 1926)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/forgottenshrines0000byne|url-access=registration|quote=mildred stapley byne.|title=Forgotten Shrines of Spain|last=Byne|first=Mrs Mildred (Stapley)|date=1926|publisher=J. B. Lippincott Company|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Important mediaeval and early Renaissance works of art from Spain: sculptures, furniture, textiles, tapestries, and rugs: collection of Conde de las Almenas, Madrid, Spain'' (New York : American Art Association, 1927), with Arthur Byne and Ercole Canessa.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/importantmediaev00amer|title=Important Mediaeval and early Renaissance works of art from Spain : sculptures, furniture, textiles, tapestries and rugs, collection of Conde de las Almenas, Madrid, Spain|last=|first=|publisher=American Art Association|others=|year=1927|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref>\n* ''The Sculptured Capital in Spain: a Series of Examples Dating from the Sixth to the Sixteenth Century'' (New York: William Helburn, Inc., 1928)\n* ''Spanish Gardens and Patios'' (New York(?): J. B. Lippincott and Co., 1928)<ref>{{Cite book|url=