n England]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav football managers]]\n[[Category:Serbian football managers]]\n[[Category:FK Partizan non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza managers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF managers]]\n[[Category:Real Oviedo managers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid managers]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona managers]]\n[[Category:RC Celta de Vigo managers]]\n[[Category:Serbia national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Shandong Luneng Taishan F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Hebei China Fortune F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Chinese Super League managers]]\n[[Category:China League One managers]]\n[[Category:2010 FIFA World Cup managers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Serbia and Montenegro expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Serbia and Montenegro expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in China]]\n[[Category:Serbian emigrants to Spain]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{additional citations}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Radomir Anti\u0107\n| image                = Radomir Anti\u0107.jpg\n| image_size           = 200px\n| caption              = Anti\u0107 pictured in 2009\n| birth_date           = {{Birth date|df=yes|1948|11|22}}\n| birth_place          = [[\u017diti\u0161te]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|FPR Yugoslavia]]\n|6 April 2020 age 71  = {{Death date cause of death =long term illness and age|df=yes|2020|04|06|1948|11|22}}\n| death_place          = [[Madrid]], [[Spain]]\n| position             = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub          =\n| years1               = 1967\u20131968  \n| clubs1               = [[FK Sloboda U\u017eice|Sloboda U\u017eice]]\n| years2               = 1968\u20131976  \n| clubs2               = [[FK Partizan|Partizan]] \n| caps2                = 181  \n| goals2               = 9 \n| years3               = 1976\u20131978  \n| clubs3               = [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]]\n| caps3                = 28   \n| goals3               = 2\n| years4               = 1978\u20131980  \n| clubs4               = [[Real Zaragoza]]\n| caps4                = 58   \n| goals4               = 7 \n| years5               = 1980\u20131984  \n| clubs5               = [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]]\n| caps5                = 100  \n| goals5               = 9 \n| totalcaps            = 367 \n| totalgoals           = 27\n| nationalyears1       = 1973  \n| nationalteam1        = [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]]\n| nationalcaps1        = 1  \n| nationalgoals1       = 0  \n| manageryears1        = 1988\u20131990\n| managerclubs1        = [[Real Zaragoza]]\n| manageryears2        = 1991\u20131992\n| managerclubs2        = [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]\n| manageryears3        = 1992\u20131995\n| managerclubs3        = [[Real Oviedo]]\n| manageryears4        = 1995\u20131998\n| managerclubs4        = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| manageryears5        = 1999\n| managerclubs5        = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| manageryears6        = 2000\n| managerclubs6        = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| manageryears7        = 2000\u20132001\n| managerclubs7        = [[Real Oviedo]]\n| manageryears8        = 2003\n| managerclubs8        = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| manageryears9        = 2004\n| managerclubs9        = [[Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]]\n| manageryears10       = 2008\u20132010\n| managerclubs10       = [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]]\n| manageryears11       = 2012\u20132013\n| managerclubs11       = [[Shandong Luneng Taishan F.C.|Shandong Luneng]]\n| manageryears12       = 2015\n| managerclubs12       = [[Hebei China Fortune F.C.|Hebei China Fortune]]\n}}\n'''Radomir Anti\u0107''' ({{lang-sr-Cyrl|\u0420\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u0410\u043d\u0442\u0438\u045b}}, {{IPA-sh|r\u01cedomi\u02d0r \u00e2\u02d0ntit\u0255|pron}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hjp.znanje.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=dl1vXhE%3D|title=r\u0203d<sup>1</sup>|quote=R\u0201dom\u012br|website=Hrvatski jezi\u010dni portal|accessdate=2018-03-17|language=sh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hjp.znanje.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=fVhlXw%3D%3D&keyword=Sv.|title=\u00c0nt\u016bn|quote=\u00c1nti\u0107|website=Hrvatski jezi\u010dni portal|accessdate=2018-03-17|language=sh}}</ref> 22 November 1948 \u2013 6 April 2020) was a Serbian professional [[Manager (association football)|football manager]] and [[Football player|player]].\n\nFollowing a 17-year playing career as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]], most of which he spent playing at [[FK Partizan|Partizan]], with whom he won the [[Yugoslav First League]], Anti\u0107 moved into coaching.\n\nHe was one of only two men to have managed both Barcelona and Real Madrid, [[El Cl\u00e1sico|long-time bitter rivals]] (the other one is [[Enrique Fern\u00e1ndez Viola]]). With [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], Anti\u0107 won the double, conquering both [[La Liga]] and the [[Copa del Rey]] in the [[1995\u201396 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|1995\u201396 season]].\n\n==Playing career==\nAnti\u0107 was born in [[\u017diti\u0161te]] to a [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Serb]] family (his father Jovo is from [[Janj]] near [[\u0160ipovo]], his mother Milka from the [[Grme\u010d]] region) that settled in the small town of [[Banat]] shortly before his birth.<ref>{{cite web |author=Veljko Lali\u0107 |url=http://www.pressonline.rs/sr/vesti/vesti_dana/story/67952/Politi%C4%8Dki+intervju+-+Radomir+Anti%C4%87%3A+Imam+taktiku+za+bolju+Srbiju.html |title=Politi\u010dki intervju \u2013 Radomir Anti\u0107: Imam taktiku za bolju Srbiju |date=7 June 2009 |language=sr |publisher=Pressonline.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124033553/http://www.pressonline.rs/sr/vesti/vesti_dana/story/67952/Politi%C4%8Dki+intervju+-+Radomir+Anti%C4%87%3A+Imam+taktiku+za+bolju+Srbiju.html |archivedate=24 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The family then moved to [[U\u017eice|Titovo U\u017eice]] when Radomir was six years old.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sport.blic.rs/Fudbal/119120/Roki-dobio-spomenik-a-Antic-bilbord |title=Roki dobio spomenik, a Anti\u0107 billboard, '&#39;Blic'&#39; |date=5 November 2009 |work=Blic |accessdate=28 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302110655/http://sport.blic.rs/Fudbal/119120/Roki-dobio-spomenik-a-Antic-bilbord |archivedate=2 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He started his playing career with [[FK Sloboda U\u017eice|Sloboda Titovo U\u017eice]] (1967\u20131968) and then moved to the club where he would play most of his career, [[FK Partizan|Partizan]] (1968\u20131976). With Partizan, he won the national Championship in 1976.\n\nIn the summer of 1976, Anti\u0107 signed for [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]] in Turkey. He spent two seasons in [[Istanbul]] before moving to the Spanish [[La Liga]], where he played for [[Real Zaragoza]].\n\nIn 1980, Anti\u0107 moved on to [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]], a team in England's [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] (which was then the second tier). Known in England as \"Raddy\", he helped Luton to the Second Division title in 1982, and stayed with the club for two seasons in the [[Football League First Division|top division]] before leaving in 1984. At the end of the [[1982\u201383 Football League|1982\u201383 season]], he played a key role in saving Luton from relegation, scoring a winning goal four minutes from time in the final League match of the season, away against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. City, the home team, were themselves relegated as a result. At full-time, Luton manager [[David Pleat]] ran across the pitch, hopping and waving his arms wildly in celebration.<ref>{{cite web|author=mattyredman |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XyAUkaC6nsI |title=Manchester City vs. Luton Town, May 1983 |publisher=Uk.youtube.com |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlready in his 30s when he arrived at Luton, Anti\u0107 already looked to coaching as a career option once his playing days are finished. While an active player in England, he enrolled in and completed the coaching college in [[Belgrade]], Vi\u0161a trenerska \u0161kola. In that regard, he often cites Pleat as an influence on his later coaching style.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130724055810/http://www.kurir-info.rs/moj-ucitelj-dejvid-plit-clanak-14439 Moj u\u010ditelj Dejvid Plit], ''Kurir'', 16 November 2009</ref>\n\nAfter helping save Luton's First Division status, Anti\u0107 spent [[1983\u201384 in English football|one more season]] at [[Kenilworth Road]] before retiring at age 36.\n\nAnti\u0107 made one appearance for the [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia national team]], appearing as a substitute in the 80th minute for injured [[Franjo Vladi\u0107]] (who himself came on as a sub for [[Vladimir Petrovi\u0107 Pi\u017eon]] some 18 minutes prior) in a friendly against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] on 26 September 1973 in Belgrade.\n\n==Managerial career==\n===Early career===\nAfter finishing his playing career at age 36, Anti\u0107 started a career in coaching as an assistant with Partizan (1985\u201387), working under head coach [[Nenad Bjekovi\u0107]]. Partizan won the [[1985\u201386 Yugoslav First League|1985\u201386 league]] title amid a match-fixing controversy. They also won the [[1986\u201387 Yugoslav First League|1986\u201387 league]].\n\nIn early July 1987, [[Fahrudin Jusufi]] was brought in as the new head coach and initially Anti\u0107 continued his assistant role. For the pre-season training ahead of the 1987\u201388 season, the team went abroad where Jusufi and Anti\u0107 got into a row over player personnel issues that resulted in Anti\u0107 being essentially demoted to the position of Partizan under-16 youth team (cadet squad) coach.\n\n===Real Zaragoza===\nAnti\u0107's first head coaching position was with Real Zaragoza. In addition to formerly playing for the club, his appointment owed a lot to being recommended for the job by countryman [[Vujadin Bo\u0161kov]], who successfully led Italian side [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] at the time, but still enjoyed a lot of clout in Spain having led Zaragoza (coached Anti\u0107 there for two years) and other La Liga clubs during the late 1970s and early '80s.\n\nThe squad was a fairly modest one without any really big names; the most notable players being the aging Spanish international midfielder [[Juan Antonio Se\u00f1or|Juan Se\u00f1or]] and forward [[Miguel Pardeza]], who came up through [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]'s youth system as part of ''[[La Quinta del Buitre]]'' generation. The club also had some young assets: a pair of 22-year-olds [[Francisco Villarroya]] and [[Juan Vizca\u00edno]] who were well on their way to becoming future Spanish internationals as well as eccentric Paraguayan goalie [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Chilavert]] who came to the club from Argentina's [[Club Atl\u00e9tico San Lorenzo de Almagro|San Lorenzo]] the same summer Anti\u0107 did. Anti\u0107's made his La Liga coaching debut on 4 September 1988 against [[Valencia CF|Valencia]], a 0\u20130 draw. The initial period was rough, with the club hovering in and around relegation zone, followed by a period of slight improvement, but still stuck in the lower half of the table. The sudden and somewhat unexpected breakthrough came during last eight league matches of the season as Anti\u0107's Zaragoza started posting win after win in a rapid climb up the table, finishing the [[1988\u201389 La Liga|season]] in fifth place, thus qualifying for the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]].\n\nHe ended up spending two full seasons (1988\u20131990) managing a club he also turned out for as a player.\n\n===Real Madrid===\nReal Madrid came calling in late March 1991 and Anti\u0107 took over from club legend [[Alfredo Di St\u00e9fano]] following ''los Merengues''' elimination from the [[1990\u201391 European Cup|European Cup]] by [[Oleg Romantsev]]'s [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]] at the quarter-final stage. Di St\u00e9fano had been on thin ice since the 1\u20130 league defeat in mid-March away to mid-table [[CD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]] (Real Madrid's third league loss in a row), but it was the 1\u20133 return leg quarter-final European Cup home loss against the Russians at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]] on 20 March 1991 that served as the last straw that prompted Di St\u00e9fano's removal. In La Liga, at the time, after 26 matches, the club occupied the seventh position in the standings.\n\nUsed to winning major trophies, the royal club was in turmoil with Anti\u0107 coming in as their third head coach of the [[1990\u201391 Real Madrid C.F. season|season]] after [[John Toshack]] and Di St\u00e9fano.\n\n==== 1990\u201391: Stopping the bleeding ====\nWith [[Emilio Butrague\u00f1o]], [[M\u00edchel (footballer)|M\u00edchel]], [[Fernando Hierro]], [[Manuel Sanch\u00eds Hontiyuelo|Manolo Sanch\u00eds]], [[Gheorghe Hagi]] and the aging [[Hugo S\u00e1nchez]] as the club's established stars, Anti\u0107's debut took place at the Bernab\u00e9u against [[Real Oviedo]] on 24 March 1991, ending in somewhat disappointing 1\u20131 draw considering Oviedo played with ten men since the 68th minute.<ref>[http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/p.php?id=18066 Real Madrid-Real Oviedo 1:1];La Liga, 24 March 1991</ref>\n\nThings would get even worse the following week with the 0\u20131 home loss to mid-table [[Real Burgos CF|Real Burgos]]<ref>[http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/p.php?id=18076 Real Madrid-Real Burgos 0:1];La Liga, 31 March 1991</ref> and downright critical the week after as Madrid was beaten 3\u20131 away at [[Luis Aragon\u00e9s]]' relegation-battling [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] by conceding two late goals,<ref>[http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/p.php?id=18085 Espanyol-Real Madrid 3:1];La Liga, 7 April 1991</ref> dropping ''los Merengues'' to the 10th spot in La Liga. After only three league matches, Anti\u0107 was feeling the full pressure of the Real hotseat.\n\nThings finally started clicking with the 4\u20130 home win versus Valencia on 14 April, that started a five-match winning streak. The 3\u20133 away draw at Osasuna ended the streak, but the team quickly put together another 3-match winning run to end the season. On 8 June, the season ended on a high note with a 1\u20130 home win against champions-elect [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in ''[[El Cl\u00e1sico]]''. In total, Anti\u0107 led Real in the final 12 league matches (8 wins, 2 draws and 2 losses) of the [[1990\u201391 La Liga|1990\u201391 season]], improving Real's standing to third in the league, and qualifying for the UEFA Cup.\nHe died in 2020\n\n==== 1991\u201392: Success and sacking ====\nDuring the 1991 summer transfer window, Anti\u0107 brought in [[Robert Prosine\u010dki]], prominent member of the [[Red Star Belgrade]]'s [[1990\u201391 European Cup|1991]] European Cup-winning side, as well as promising 21-year-old [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Lu\u00eds Enrique]] from [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n]].\n\nAnti\u0107's team began the season in furious fashion with five straight [[1991\u201392 La Liga|league]] wins, grabbing the La Liga top spot ahead of ''El Cl\u00e1sico'' on 19 October 1991. Playing [[Johan Cruyff]]'s ''Bar\u00e7a'' \"dream team\" at home at the Bernab\u00e9u, Real went ahead via a Prosine\u010dki first half free-kick, one shining moment in the highly rated signing's otherwise disastrous season, before [[Ronald Koeman]] equalized courtesy of a second half penalty shot.<ref>[http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/p.php?id=18066 Real Madrid-FC Barcelona 1:1];La Liga, 19 October 1991</ref> Real's winning streak in the league had thus been broken, however, with the very next league match, a 3\u20130 home win over Logro\u00f1\u00e9s,<ref>[http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/p.php?id=18265 Real Madrid-CD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s 3:0];La Liga, 27 October 1991</ref> ''los Merengues'' commenced another winning streak, this time recording seven straight league wins as they tangibly separated themselves from the pack of chasers atop the La Liga standings.\n\nOne player especially excelled under Anti\u0107: 23-year-old Hierro, normally a defender, was moved up further into midfield and responded by scoring in numbers, eventually ending the season on 21 league goals, the greatest single-season offensive output of his career. The second winning streak in the league ended with a draw away at Zaragoza in mid-December 1991.<ref>[http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/p.php?id=18339 Real Zaragoza-Real Madrid 1:1];La Liga, 15 December 1991</ref> This was followed by a slight dip in form as Real recorded another draw the following week at home against Oviedo, before experiencing its first league loss of the season away at cross-town rivals [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], though still retaining top league spot by a comfortable margin. During this three-match period without a league win, club president [[Ram\u00f3n Mendoza]] opted to bring [[Leo Beenhakker]] into the organization in a vaguely defined sporting director role, though Anti\u0107 remained the team's head coach. The three-match winless streak ended with an emphatic 5\u20132 win at home versus [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]], but was followed by the second league loss of the season when [[Guus Hiddink]]'s Valencia managed to overturn Real's 0\u20131 lead with two late goals and record a famous home win over the league leaders.<ref>[http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/p.php?id=18370 Valencia CF-Real Madrid 2:1];La Liga, 18 January 1992</ref> Although Anti\u0107's team quickly got back on winning track with a 2\u20131 home win against [[CD Tenerife|Tenerife]] on 26 January 1992,<ref>[http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/p.php?id=18388 Real Madrid-CD Tenerife 2:1];La Liga, 26 January 1992</ref> the 43-year-old coach was terminated. At the time of Anti\u0107's termination, 19 league matches into the season, Madrid was holding the top spot in La Liga by a seven-point margin and was also smoothly through to the [[1991\u201392 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] quarter-finals with previous wins over [[\u0160K Slovan Bratislava|Slovan Bratislava]], [[FC Utrecht|Utrecht]] and [[Neuch\u00e2tel Xamax]].\n\nLed by Beenhakker, Real Madrid squandered its seven-point lead, losing the title to bitter rivals Barcelona on the last matchday of the season. Madrid was also eliminated from UEFA Cup by [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] in the semi-finals.\n\n===Real Oviedo===\nAnti\u0107 was hired to coach Real Oviedo when the club's brass fired previous longtime coach [[Javier Irureta]] after matchday 19 of the [[1992\u201393 La Liga|1992\u201393 season]] with the club dangerously close to the relegation zone in 16th spot and a one match stint of caretaker Julio Marigil Mar\u00edn. Anti\u0107 took over from matchday 21 and completed the season with the club, managing to avoid relegation by finishing two spots above the relegation zone. He remained at the club for two additional seasons.\n\nDuring the 1993 summer transfer window, Anti\u0107 signed [[Slavi\u0161a Jokanovi\u0107]] from Partizan, whose midfield presence greatly helped the squad. The expectations at Oviedo were obviously much more modest compared to Real Madrid, with mere top league survival being the main goal. It was therefore no small surprise that a very low budget Anti\u0107-led Oviedo team finished the [[1993\u201394 La Liga|1993\u201394]] league season in ninth place.\n\nAnti\u0107's most notable signing at Oviedo came before the start of [[1994\u201395 La Liga|1994\u201395 season]] when he brought often injured Robert Prosine\u010dki from Real Madrid, thus reuniting with a player he first signed to Madrid. Oviedo again finished the La Liga season in respectable ninth position, missing a European spot by mere points.\n\n===Atl\u00e9tico Madrid===\nAnti\u0107's greatest coaching successes are tied to Atl\u00e9tico Madrid, a club he ended up coaching in three separate stints.\n\nHis achievements with transforming Oviedo's fortunes led to offers from bigger Spanish clubs. Despite having been in final stages of the negotiations with Valencia with even a pre-contract signed, Anti\u0107 opted to take the offer by Atl\u00e9tico club president [[Jes\u00fas Gil]], leading to the Serb's first engagement with the club that ended up lasting three seasons (1995\u201398). The squad he took over during summer 1995 was a talented one featuring the quality core of [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Caminero]], [[Kiko Narv\u00e1ez]] and [[Diego Simeone]], but with a reputation of continuous underachievement. In the [[1994\u201395 La Liga|season prior to his arrival]], the club finished one point above relegation zone by earning a 2\u20132 draw versus [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] on the last matchday of the season.\n\n==== 1995\u201396: Double title ====\nOut of the 35-player squad he inherited, Anti\u0107 quickly identified 20 players he was counting on for the following season before setting about adding five to six more players during the transfer window. That meant the end of Atl\u00e9tico days for a slew of players including aging goalie [[Abel Resino]], embattled Colombian striker [[Adolfo Valencia]], Brazilian [[Iv\u00e1n Rocha]], Polish striker [[Roman Kosecki]] and Russian winger [[Igor Dobrovolski]], among others.\n\nFirst on Anti\u0107's wish list was defender [[Viktor Onopko]] whom he coached at Real Oviedo: Atl\u00e9tico and the player agreed terms, however, Oviedo management were not satisfied and the case ended up before a [[FIFA]] arbitration commission, which ruled in Oviedo's favour. Anti\u0107 then tried to sign 19-year-old [[Fernando Morientes]] from [[Albacete Balompi\u00e9|Albacete]], but the talented striker instead signed with Zaragoza.<ref>{{cite web|last=Antic |first=Radomir |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/4167681.stm |title=Morientes to cast off Ronaldo shadow |publisher=BBC News  |date=12 January 2005 |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> Out of the players Anti\u0107 did manage to sign, the biggest find turned out to be unheralded winger [[Milinko Panti\u0107]], whom Anti\u0107 plucked from obscurity in [[Panionios F.C.|Panionios]] for very little money. The move initially raised eyebrows with many questioning the usefulness of a complete unknown who is about to turn 29 years of age, however over the coming season, Panti\u0107 would prove himself to be the missing piece this team needed with key goals and assists. Another key acquisition was 29-year-old Bulgarian tall centre forward [[Luboslav Penev]], brought in from Valencia despite questions about his health due to a recent bout with [[testicular cancer]]. Other incoming transfers included goalkeeper [[Jos\u00e9 Francisco Molina]] and central defender [[Santiago Denia|Santi Denia]] from Albacete, midfielder [[Roberto Fresnedoso]] from Espanyol and young Argentine striker [[Leonardo Biagini|Leo Biagini]] from [[Newell's Old Boys]], who starred at the [[1995 FIFA World Youth Championship]].\n\nPlaying in the domestic league that was just expanded from 20 to 22 teams along with a new points system with three points awarded for a win, under Anti\u0107's command, the Atl\u00e9tico squad featuring Molina in goal, [[Delf\u00ed Geli]] and Santi Denia in central defence, [[Roberto Soloz\u00e1bal]] and [[Antonio Mu\u00f1oz G\u00f3mez|Toni]] on right and left back respectively, [[Juan Vizca\u00edno]] (whom Anti\u0107 previously coached at Zaragoza) and Caminero in centre midfield, Simeone and Panti\u0107 on right and left wing respectively, and finally Penev and Kiko upfront gelled together masterfully en route to a historic [[La Liga]]/[[Copa del Rey]] double in the [[1995\u201396 Atl\u00e9tico Madrid season|1995\u201396 season]]. Other players that didn't start as often, but nevertheless contributed significantly throughout the season were Fresnedoso, [[Juan Manuel L\u00f3pez (footballer)|Juan Manuel L\u00f3pez]], Biagini, [[Francisco Javier Mori|Pirri Mori]], etc.\n\nAnti\u0107's Atl\u00e9tico began the league campaign in furious fashion with four impressive wins. Once they took the top league spot after week 2, ''los Colchoneros'' gave it up only once (after the week 5 scoreless draw at Sevilla), before reclaiming it the very next week and impressively continuing on top until the end with Penev scoring 16 league goals, Simeone 12, Kiko 11, Panti\u0107 10, and Caminero 9. Atl\u00e9tico also featured a stingy defence that allowed 32 goals \u2013 less than any other team in the league. Still, the title wasn't secure until the very last match, as Valencia stayed in close pursuit until the end. Going into the last round of matches on Saturday 25 May 1996, Atl\u00e9tico was on 84 points with Alabacete to play at home while Valencia had 82 and Celta away. The victory was never in doubt as Simeone and Kiko scored in the first half sparking off jubilant scenes at [[Vicente Calder\u00f3n Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Zarateh64 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IiJ-tXfJyzQ |title=Atl\u00e9tico Madrid-Albacete |date= 25 May 1996 |work=Youtube |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nMonth and a half earlier Anti\u0107 already claimed his first trophy of the season, beating [[Johan Cruyff]]'s Bar\u00e7a in the [[Copa del Rey]] [[1996 Copa del Rey Final|final]] in [[Zaragoza]] after extra time on a goal by Panti\u0107.\n\nWinning the double endeared Anti\u0107 to Atl\u00e9tico faithful and more importantly to club's controversial president [[Jes\u00fas Gil]]. Notorious for quickly and impulsively going through coaches, Gil kept Anti\u0107 at the helm of his team for two more seasons (three consecutive seasons in total) \u2013 a record of sorts considering Gil's trigger-happy nature when it came to gaffers.\n\n==== 1996\u201397: Champions League participation ====\nDuring the 1996 summer transfer window, the squad upgrade was in order ahead of the 1996\u201397 season that saw Atl\u00e9tico compete in the [[1996\u201397 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] in addition to [[1996\u201397 La Liga|defending the La Liga title]].\n\nAs replacement for aging Luboslav Penev who was impressive during the double title season despite simultaneously recovering and also as general statement of intent for the coming season, Atl\u00e9tico was in the market for a marquee forward. Anti\u0107 wanted to bring in promising 19-year-old Brazilian striker [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]] from [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] and pushed hard within the club hierarchy for that to be done.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/video/video.php?nav_category=899&nav_id=353706 |title=Poligraf Plus, B92, |date= 3 April 2009 |publisher=B92.net |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> However, he ultimately got overruled by higher instances and Ronaldo signed with Barcelona about a month later. Instead, Atl\u00e9tico acquired 23-year-old Argentine striker [[Juan Esn\u00e1ider]] from Real Madrid. Another big acquisition was 24-year-old Czech defensive midfielder [[Radek Bejbl]] from [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]], who was coming off a great showing at [[UEFA Euro 1996]] where Czechs finished runners-up. The arrival of Bejbl meant that 30-year-old Vizca\u00edno lost his starting spot in defensive midfield.\n\nSimultaneously playing on two difficult fronts proved to be much more demanding and the team quickly started lagging behind Real and Barcelona in La Liga, while in the Champions League they progressed to the quarter-finals on top of the group featuring [[Borussia Dortmund]], [[Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] and [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]]. In the second part of league campaign Atl\u00e9tico somewhat steadied its form, but was unable to make up the minus from early part of the season. In Champions League, the quarter-final clash against [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] turned into an epic battle with tensions often spilling outside the pitch like when Jes\u00fas Gil publicly referred to Ajax as \"FC Congo\" due to the large number of black players of African and Surinamese origin on their team. Atl\u00e9tico achieved a great 1\u20131 result away as Esn\u00e1ider scored a header after fine work from Delf\u00ed Geli on the right.<ref>{{YouTube|quYhF_snPMc|Ajax-Atetico Esnaider goal}}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref> The return leg in Madrid was a tense affair that saw ''los Colchoneros'' go up through Kiko in the first half before Overmars equalized just after halftime. With the score tied at one a piece and the match heading into extra-time, Anti\u0107 decided to put Biagini on instead of Esn\u00e1ider who was not pleased about the substitution and got into a vicious shouting match with the coach as he exited the pitch.<ref>{{YouTube|u8y1YIpQiuM|Esn\u00e1ider-Anti\u0107 verbal duel}}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref> Ten minutes into the extra period, Ajax's Portuguese forward [[Daniel da Cruz Carvalho|Dani]] scored on a beautiful effort for 1\u20132,<ref>{{YouTube|DHbzT9s1ig0|Dani scores for 1\u20132}}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref> which meant that due to away-goals, Atl\u00e9tico would now have to score twice more to go through. Within five minutes they got a penalty, which Panti\u0107 converted, but couldn't manage one more goal despite attacking in waves for the remaining fifteen minutes. Due to Atl\u00e9tico's all out attack, Ajax even scored a third goal on the quick counter-attack through [[Tijani Babangida]].\n\n==== 1997\u201398: Heavy spending ====\nAhead of the [[1997\u201398 La Liga|1997\u201398 season]], Gil invested heavily into the team, bringing 24-year-old Italian superstar [[Christian Vieri]] fresh from winning the [[Serie A]] title with [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. He also bought crafty 25-year-old Brazilian [[Juninho Paulista|Juninho]] from [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] for [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]12&nbsp;million. In order to somewhat offset the costs, inspirational midfielder Diego Simeone was sold to [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]]. Naturally the expectations were high, with spotlight especially focused on expensive new signings. Though both struggled with injuries causing them to miss significant chunk of the season, Vieri still managed to produce excellent form when fit to play with 24 goals in 24 league appearances, while Juninho struggled to make similar impact with only 6 goals in 23 league appearances.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=728936&sec=england&root=england&cc=5901 Juninho: Samba star]; ESPN Soccernet, 22 January 2010</ref> When Atletico started sputtering in La Liga, the rumblings about Anti\u0107's possible dismissal were heard for the first time. When Atl\u00e9tico got eliminated by [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] at the semi-final stage of [[1997\u201398 UEFA Cup]], Gil launched into an obscenity-laced tirade against Spanish television for reporting he has lined up an Italian coach to replace Anti\u0107.\n\nIn the end, that is exactly what happened as he was let go at season's end during the summer of 1998 to make way for [[Arrigo Sacchi]].\n\n===Return to Atl\u00e9tico===\nAnti\u0107, however, would not be away from Atl\u00e9tico for long, as Sacchi got sacked midway through 1998\u201399 season after matchday 22, and following a five-match stint of caretaker coach [[Carlos S\u00e1nchez Aguiar]], the Serb returned for a second spell that lasted from matchday 28 until the end of the season (11 league matches). With Atl\u00e9tico clinging to lowly 13th spot in league standings when Anti\u0107 returned, the repeat of league success proved elusive as the team recorded three wins, four losses and four draws under his command to finish the season in the same 13th place. Anti\u0107, however, managed to inspire the team all the way to [[1999 Copa del Rey Final|1999 Copa del Rey final]] at the freshly opened [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico de Sevilla|La Cartuja Stadium]] in [[Seville]], where they lost heavily to [[Claudio Ranieri]]'s Valencia, 0\u20133.\n\nAnti\u0107 was again let go at season's end, and eventually replaced with Ranieri.\n\n===Third time at Atl\u00e9tico===\nAnti\u0107's third stint at the club, which came during the second part of [[1999\u20132000 La Liga|1999\u20132000 season]] (started in February 2000) turned out to be the most difficult. Following Ranieri's dismissal after matchday 26 with the club in administration due to accumulated debts, Anti\u0107 took over a squad that was already in a tailspin, sitting in 17th league spot barely hovering above relegation zone.\n\nAnti\u0107's third arrival to the club ahead of matchday 27 did little to change matters as Atl\u00e9tico lost on his return, falling back into the relegation zone and never coming out of it until the end of the season. Despite the goalscoring exploits of [[Jimmy Floyd Hasselbaink]], they were eliminated from [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Cup]] at the eight-final stage by [[RC Lens|Lens]], but [[1999\u20132000 La Liga|relegation from La Liga]] several months later came as the most painful blow of all. Anti\u0107 was terminated after matchday 37 after Atl\u00e9tico was already mathematically relegated with one league match left in the season; for the final match, the team was coached by [[Fernando Zambrano]].\n\nMaking the Copa del Rey final for the second consecutive season came as one bright spot in an otherwise disastrous season, but even that was not to be as they were beaten to the trophy by Espanyol.\n\n===Return to Real Oviedo===\nAnti\u0107 returned to Real Oviedo in the summer of 2000. His team suffered their first relegation for 13 years, and he was sacked on 6 July 2001.<ref>{{cite news |title=El Oviedo despide a Antic |url=https://as.com/futbol/2001/07/06/mas_futbol/994370402_850215.html |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Diario AS |date=6 July 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Barcelona===\nAfter taking a year and a half long break from coaching, Anti\u0107 joined Barcelona in late January 2003 on initiative by club president [[Joan Gaspart]] to take over from recently sacked [[Louis van Gaal]]. Caretaker head coach [[Antonio de la Cruz]] took temporary charge of team affairs until Anti\u0107 took the reins with the team occupying the 15th spot in the Liga standings with only 23 points from 20 league matches (six wins, five draws and nine losses), but well placed in the Champions League [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League second group stage|second phase]] with two wins from as many matches. The club's league position was so weak that mere top-flight survival was put forth as Anti\u0107's immediate goal. On the other hand, in Champions League, the expectations were substantial. Some press outlets reported that his six-month \u20ac600,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs/arhiva/2003/02/02/srpski/S03020103.shtml |title=Barselona \u0107e upoznati novog Anti\u0107a!, '&#39;Glas javnosti'&#39; |date= 2 February 2003 |publisher=Arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> contract with ''Bar\u00e7a'' was incentive based, stipulating automatic one-year extension at the end of the season if the club qualifies for the following season's Champions League based on the domestic league finish (top-four).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs/arhiva/2003/02/01/srpski/S03013101.shtml |title=Barselona izabrala Radomira Anti\u0107a!, '&#39;Glas javnosti'&#39;|date= 1 February 2003 |publisher=Arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nAnti\u0107 immediately brought in [[Juan Pablo Sor\u00edn]] from Lazio. He also started giving regular first team appearances to young goalkeeper [[V\u00edctor Vald\u00e9s]] as well as throwing another youngster, [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]], into the first team. Additionally, Anti\u0107 moved [[Xavi]] further up the field, just behind the line of forwards thus freeing him up from the defensive duties he had under Van Gaal, which allowed the diminutive midfielder to fully showcase his creativity.<ref>[http://www.kurir-info.rs/sport/cavi-antic-me-napravio-68287.php Jedan od najboljih fudbalera dana\u0161njice \u0106avi u autobiografskom romanu odao priznanje biv\u0161em srpskom selektoru] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110109002624/http://www.kurir-info.rs/sport/cavi-antic-me-napravio-68287.php |date=9 January 2011 }};''Kurir'', 6 January 2010</ref> \n\nAnti\u0107 managed to stabilize the squad and lead it to sixth-place Liga finish, ensuring UEFA Cup qualification. His record with the club in the season since taking over was nine wins, six draws and three losses. In the Champions League, under Anti\u0107 ''Bar\u00e7a'' dominated their group in the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League second group stage|Second Group Stage]] throughout February and early March, which gave the team a much needed confidence boost for the rest of the season on all fronts.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/antic-glows-as-barcelona-earn-respect-600398.html Antic glows as Barcelona earn respect], ''The Independent'', 13 March 2003</ref> In fact, just his third match in charge of ''Bar\u00e7a'' was an important Champions League clash at home versus Inter that the Catalans ended up winning 3\u20130, thus marking the coach's return to the Champions League after six years and also extending the team's win streak to 11 consecutive Champions League matches, breaking the previous record by [[A.C. Milan|Milan]].<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200302/s787716.htm Antic delighted with record-breaking Barca]{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}; ABC News Online, 19 February 2003</ref><ref>{{YouTube|sQiZiPZL9Ro|Barca-Inter 3\u20130}}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref> Anti\u0107's Barcelona, however, lost in extra time of the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League knockout stage|quarter-final]] to [[Marcello Lippi]]'s Juventus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Juve break Barca hearts |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/2958995.stm |accessdate=6 April 2020 |date=22 April 2003}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 June 2003, it was announced by new club president [[Joan Laporta]] that the optional second year in Anti\u0107's contract would not be activated, and [[Frank Rijkaard]] was appointed in his place.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rijkaard replaces Antic at Bar\u00e7a |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/025a-0eaacc8e0fff-61ac44f5ecae-1000--rijkaard-replaces-antic-at-barca/?referrer=%2Fuefaeuropaleague%2Fnews%2Fnewsid%3D76312 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=23 June 2003}}</ref>\n\n===Celta de Vigo===\nOn 29 January 2004, Anti\u0107 succeeded [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Lotina]] at an [[RC Celta de Vigo]] side one point and one place above the relegation places.<ref>{{cite news |title=Antic introduced at Celta |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/football/la-liga/2003-2004/antic-introduced-at-celta_sto540072/story.shtml |accessdate=6 April 2020 |publisher=Eurosport |date=29 January 2004}}</ref> He lost 1\u20130 away to [[Real Betis]] on his debut. Following this match in which he felt Celta deserved a more positive result, Anti\u0107 identified overturning the loss of self-confidence among some of his players due to club's weak league position as his biggest challenge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arhiva.kurir-info.rs/Arhiva/2004/februar/04/SP-02-03022004.shtml |title=Peti izazov Radomira Anti\u0107a |date= 4 February 2004 |publisher=Arhiva.kurir-info.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> \n\nExactly two months after his hiring, Anti\u0107 quit Celta, who were now second from bottom. He took seven points from his nine league games, and was eliminated from the Champions League last 16 by [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Antic quits Celta |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/3580921.stm |accessdate=6 April 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 March 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Serbian national team===\nOn 19 August 2008, it was reported in the Serbian media that Anti\u0107 agreed terms with the [[Football Association of Serbia|Serbian Football Association]] (FSS) to take over his native country's national team. On 25 August, he was officially unveiled as the new head coach. The appointment came in somewhat controversial circumstances, as previous head coach [[Miroslav \u0110uki\u0107]] was being fired following a disastrous [[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2008 Olympic campaign]] and \u0110uki\u0107's public feuding with FSS president [[Tomislav Karad\u017ei\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mondo.rs/a108824/Sport/Fudbal/Djukic-Ajmo-Djoricu-ajmo-Karadzicu.html |title=\u0110uki\u0107: Ajmo \u0110ori\u0107u, ajmo Karad\u017ei\u0107u... |date= 21 August 2008 |publisher=Mtsmondo.com |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> \n\nThe appointment also marked 59-year-old Anti\u0107's return to coaching after four years. According to both Anti\u0107 and Karad\u017ei\u0107, the negotiations between the coach and the FSS were very short and the agreement was reached quickly after Anti\u0107's only conditions that he brings in his own support staff and that his second in command is his long-time collaborator [[Re\u0161ad Kunovac]] were accepted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politika.rs/rubrike/Sport/intervjui/Imali-smo-igracha-vishe-u-Borisu-Tadicu.sr.html |title=Karadzic Interview, April 5, 2009 |publisher=Politika.rs |date=18 April 2009 |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> Anti\u0107's initial salary was reportedly somewhere in the range of \u20ac305,000 to \u20ac325,000 per year, along with a \u20ac500,000 bonus incentive if the team qualified for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futebolfinance.com/en/os-salarios-dos-treinadores-no-mundial-2010/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111109100014/http://www.futebolfinance.com/os-salarios-dos-treinadores-no-mundial-2010|archivedate=2011-11-09 |title=Salaries of coaches in the World 2010 |publisher=Futebolfinance.com |date=14 December 2009 |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/sport/fudbal/vesti.php?yyyy=2009&mm=12&dd=11&nav_id=397852 |title=SP: Anti\u0107 23. po visini plate, B92, Dec. 10, 2009 |publisher=B92.net |date=24 November 2011 |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=M.Stani\u0107 |url=http://www.pressonline.rs/sr/vesti/sport/story/88054/Anti%C4%87u+plata+500.000+evra+godi%C5%A1nje!.html |title=Anti\u0107u plata 500.000 evra godi\u0161nje! |date=21 November 2009 |language=sr |publisher=Pressonline.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> Anti\u0107's annual earnings from the job were thus less than [[Javier Clemente]]'s \u20ac360,000 per year salary when the [[Basque people|Basque]] was the Serbian team's head coach from 2006 until 2007.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120912224058/http://www.politika.rs/detaljno.php?nid=5608 Clemente: I'm proud of my work in Serbia] by [[Politika]]. Retrieved 2 July 2008</ref>\n\nHis debut was on 6 September 2008 in a qualifier against the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] at the [[Red Star Stadium|Marakana Stadium]], a 2\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sport.blic.rs/Fudbal/55938/Pamtice-se-samo-rezultat-Srbija-pobedila-sa-20 |title=Pamti\u0107e se samo rezultat: Srbija pobedila sa 2:0, '&#39;Blic'&#39; |date=6 September 2008 |work=Blic |accessdate=28 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302110712/http://sport.blic.rs/Fudbal/55938/Pamtice-se-samo-rezultat-Srbija-pobedila-sa-20 |archivedate=2 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In his first qualifying campaign managing Serbia, Anti\u0107 led the team to first place in their group for the 2010 World Cup. After successful qualification, it was reported in November 2009 (amid reports of icy relations between Anti\u0107 and FSS president Karad\u017ei\u0107<ref>{{cite web |author=Milovan Stani\u0107,Novak \u0110urovi\u0107 |url=http://www.pressonline.co.rs/sr/vesti/sport/story/87388/+Karad%C5%BEi%C4%87:+Anti%C4%87+i+ja+nismo+u+sva%C4%91i!.html |title=Karad\u017ei\u0107: Anti\u0107 i ja nismo u sva\u0111i!, '&#39;Press'&#39;, |date=17 November 2009 |language=sr |publisher=Pressonline.co.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301170012/http://www.pressonline.co.rs/sr/vesti/sport/story/87388/+Karad%C5%BEi%C4%87%3A+Anti%C4%87+i+ja+nismo+u+sva%C4%91i%21.html |archivedate=1 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>) that Anti\u0107 and FSS agreed a new contract.<ref>{{cite web|author=Zoran Stojadinovi\u0107 |url=http://www.politika.rs/rubrike/Sport/fudbal/Karadzic-Antic-selektor-do-2012.lt.html |title=Karad\u017ei\u0107: Anti\u0107 selektor do 2012!, '&#39;Politika'&#39;, |date=20 November 2009 |publisher=Politika.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> Over the coming weeks, Anti\u0107's new base salary became the subject of rife press speculation putting the new sum anywhere from \u20ac528,000 per year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/sport/fudbal/vesti.php?yyyy=2009&mm=12&dd=11&nav_id=397852 |title=Anti\u0107u 44 hiljade evra mese\u010dno?, B92, December 11, 2009 |publisher=B92.net |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> to \u20ac1.2&nbsp;million per year.<ref>{{cite web |author=M. Stani\u0107 |url=http://www.pressonline.rs/sr/jar2010/Srbija/story/91256/Anti%C4%87+potpisuje+za+platu+od+100.000+evra!.html |title=Anti\u0107 potpisuje za platu od 100.000 evra! |date=11 December 2009 |language=sr |publisher=Pressonline.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124033358/http://www.pressonline.rs/sr/jar2010/Srbija/story/91256/Anti%C4%87+potpisuje+za+platu+od+100.000+evra%21.html |archivedate=24 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Since the contract was not formally signed and announced by mid-December, despite assurances, even by Anti\u0107's agent [[Mi\u0161ko Ra\u017enatovi\u0107]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politika.rs/rubrike/Sport/sportske-price/Turci-nudili-Anticu-chetiri-puta-vishe-para.lt.html |title=Turci nudili Anti\u0107u \u010detiri puta vi\u0161e para, '&#39;Politika'&#39;, |date=11 December 2009 |publisher=Politika.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> that it will happen any day now, the reports of Anti\u0107\u2013Karad\u017ei\u0107 feud reignited,<ref>{{cite web|author=M. Stani\u0107 |url=http://www.pressonline.rs/sr/vesti/sport/story/91565/Anti%C4%87+opet+ljut+na+Toleta.html |title=Anti\u0107 opet ljut na Toleta, '&#39;Press'&#39; |date=13 December 2009 |language=sr |publisher=Pressonline.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311060905/http://www.pressonline.rs/sr/vesti/sport/story/91565/Anti%C4%87+opet+ljut+na+Toleta.html |archivedate=11 March 2012 }}</ref> especially when irritated Anti\u0107 himself flippantly claimed that he did not know anything about a new contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mondo.rs/s155360/Antic-_Muka_mi_je.html |title=Anti\u0107: Muka mi je..., mondo.rs, |date=12 December 2009 |publisher=Mondo.rs |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> Eventually, on 18 December 2009, Anti\u0107's new contract was announced, extending his term to 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/sport/fudbal/vesti.php?yyyy=2009&mm=12&dd=18&nav_id=399108 |title=Anti\u0107 vodi 'Orlove' do 2012. godine, B92, |date=18 December 2009 |publisher=B92.net |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring early part of 2010, in addition to his regular assistants, Anti\u0107 added experienced globetrotting Serbian coach [[Bora Milutinovi\u0107]] in the adviser role. Milutinovi\u0107 in turn brought along his long-time assistant, Chilean [[Julio C\u00e9sar Moreno]].<ref>[http://www.mondo.rs/s174839/Mundijal_2010/Cileanac_Moreno-_Ja_sam_Srbin.html \u010cileanac Moreno: Ja sam Srbin]; MTS Mondo, 29 June 2010</ref> Anti\u0107 mostly relied on them for opponent scouting.\n\nAt the 2010 World Cup in South Africa, Serbia began with a 1\u20130 loss to [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]], but followed it up with a surprise 1\u20130 win over [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Daniel |title=Germany lose to Serbia after Klose's red card and Podolski's penalty miss |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/18/germany-serbia-world-cup-match-report |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=18 June 2010}}</ref> A 2\u20131 loss to [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] in the final group game meant both countries went home.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fletcher |first1=Paul |title=Australia 2-1 Serbia |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_40/default.stm |accessdate=6 April 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nAnti\u0107 received a four-match ban for his behaviour in the Australia match, and was sacked on 15 September 2010 after a poor start to [[UEFA Euro 2012]] qualifying in his absence.<ref>{{cite news |title=Serbia sack Radomir Antic and recruit Vladimir Petrovic |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9002826.stm |accessdate=6 April 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Shandong Luneng Taishan ===\nOn 25 December 2012, it was announced that Anti\u0107 signed a two-year contract with [[Chinese Super League]] side [[Shandong Luneng Taishan F.C.|Shandong Luneng Taishan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lnts.com.cn/portal.php?mod=view&aid=2610 |title=\u9c81\u80fd\u8db3\u7403\u4ff1\u4e50\u90e8\u4e0e\u5b89\u8482\u5947\u6b63\u5f0f\u7b7e\u7ea6(Shandong Luneng sign with Anti\u0107) |date=25 December 2012 |publisher=Shandong Luneng Taishan official website |accessdate=25 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6FHd1MOay?url=http://www.lnts.com.cn/portal.php?mod=view&aid=2610 |archivedate=21 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> with [[Aleksandar Rogic]] as his assistant.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/sport.294.html:412473-%D0%92%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%BC%D0%B5%D0%B7%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%B8%D1%9B-%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B0%D0%BE-%D0%B1%D0%B5%D0%B7-%D1%81%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B4%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%B0 | title=Vermezovi\u0107 ostao bez saradnika | language=Serbian | publisher=Novosti | date=27 December 2012 | accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> Although leading Shandong Luneng (which had finished in 12th position in the 2012 season) to second place in the league, he was released by Shandong on 21 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lnts.com.cn/portal.php?mod=view&aid=3384 |title=\u5b98\u65b9\u8d44\u8baf |date=21 December 2012 |publisher=Shandong Luneng Taishan official website |accessdate=30 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221100223/http://www.lnts.com.cn/portal.php?mod=view&aid=3384 |archivedate=21 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Hebei Zhongji ===\nOn 27 January 2015, he signed a three-year contract with [[China League One]] side [[Hebei Zhongji F.C.|Hebei Zhongji]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.sohu.com/20150127/n408107306.shtml|script-title=zh:\u6cb3\u5317\u4e2d\u57fa\u66f4\u540d\u6cb3\u5317\u534e\u590f\u5e78\u798f \u5b89\u8482\u5947\u4e0a\u4efb\u7b7e\u7ea6\u4e09\u5e74|publisher=sohu.com |date=27 January 2015 |accessdate=27 January 2015|language=zh}}</ref> He was sacked on 18 August after not leading the club into the promotion zone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/b/2015-08-18/doc-ifxfxzzn7560743.shtml|script-title=zh:\u6cb3\u5317\u534e\u590f\u5ba3\u5e03\u5b89\u8482\u5947\u4e0b\u8bfe \u674e\u94c1\u6210\u65b0\u4efb\u4e3b\u5e05|publisher=sina.com |date=18 August 2015 |accessdate=18 August 2015|language=zh}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nDuring the 1995\u201396 double title season in Spain, Anti\u0107 had a notable public spat with Spanish political columnist [[Hermann Tertsch]] of the daily, ''[[El Pa\u00eds]]''. In an interview with journalist [[Carmen Rigalt]] that was published on 10 September 1995 in ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'', Anti\u0107 took issue with the views expressed by Tertsch. Considering Tertsch's political views to be anti-Serbian, Anti\u0107 called him a \"Nazi\". Tertsch in turn sued Anti\u0107 for [[libel]] and received a court ruling in his favour in the amount of [[Spanish peseta|ESP]]2&nbsp;million. Following appeals, the case even went before the [[Spanish Supreme Court]] that confirmed in mid-November 2003 the original ruling in Tertsch's favour, thus ordering Anti\u0107 to pay the [[euro]] equivalent of the originally awarded amount, approximately \u20ac12,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/sociedad/Supremo/condena/Antic/llamar/nazi/periodista/Hermann/Tertsch/elpepisoc/20031111elpepisoc_12/Tes |title=El Supremo condena a Antic por llamar \"nazi\" al periodista Hermann Tertsch | date=11 November 2003 |publisher=Elpais.com |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|18 August 2015}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Real Zaragoza]]\n|align=left|1 July 1988\n|align=left|30 June 1990\n{{WDL|86|35|24|27|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]\n|align=left|21 March 1991\n|align=left|27 January 1992\n{{WDL|39|27|6|6|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Real Oviedo]]\n|align=left|5 February 1993\n|align=left|30 June 1995\n{{WDL|112|41|31|40|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n|align=left|1 July 1995\n|align=left|30 June 1998\n{{WDL|157|81|41|35|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n|align=left|24 March 1999\n|align=left|30 June 1999\n{{WDL|14|4|5|5|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n|align=left|4 March 2000\n|align=left|15 May 2000\n{{WDL|15|2|5|8|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Real Oviedo]]\n|align=left|1 July 2000\n|align=left|30 June 2001\n{{WDL|39|11|8|20|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n|align=left|7 February 2003\n|align=left|30 June 2003\n{{WDL|24|12|8|4|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]]\n|align=left|29 January 2004\n|align=left|29 March 2004\n{{WDL|10|1|1|8|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|-\n|align=left|[[Serbia national football team|Serbia]]\n|align=left|20 August 2008\n|align=left|15 September 2010\n{{WDL|28|17|3|8|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Shandong Luneng Taishan F.C.|Shandong Luneng]]\n|align=left|24 December 2012\n|align=left|21 December 2013\n{{WDL|32|19|5|8|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Hebei China Fortune F.C.|Hebei China Fortune]]\n|align=left|27 January 2015\n|align=left|18 August 2015\n{{WDL|23|11|5|7|decimals=2}}\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|579|261|142|176|decimals=2}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nAnti\u0107 lived in [[Madrid]]<ref>[http://sport.blic.rs/Fudbal/171073/Kuca-u-Madridu-je-nas-mali-raj- Ku\u0107a u Madridu je na\u0161 mali raj] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115181949/http://sport.blic.rs/Fudbal/171073/Kuca-u-Madridu-je-nas-mali-raj- |date=15 January 2010 }}; ''Blic'', 13 January 2010</ref> and [[Marbella]] in Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mondo.rs/a77118/Sport/Fudbal/MONDO-u-poseti-kod-Radomira-Antica.html |title=MONDO u poseti kod\u2026 Radomira Anti\u0107a |date=24 October 2007 |publisher=Mtsmondo.com |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe died on 6 April 2020 in Madrid, aged 71, due to pancreatitis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Munday |first1=Billy |title=Radomir Antic dies aged 71 |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2020/04/06/5e449d5dca4741b5028b45b2.html |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Marca |date=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|title=Preminuo Radomir Anti\u0107 \n|url=https://www.b92.net/sport/fudbal/vesti.php?yyyy=2020&mm=04&dd=06&nav_id=1673067 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=B92 |date=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fallece el exentrenador Radomir Antic |url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/20200406/48356413005/radomir-antic-atletico-jesus-gil-doblete-entrenador.html |website=La Vanguardia |accessdate=6 April 2020 |language=es |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Partizan''' \n*[[Yugoslav First League]]: [[1975\u201376 Yugoslav First League|1975\u201376]]\n\n===Manager===\n'''Atl\u00e9tico Madrid''' \n*[[La Liga]]: [[1995\u201396 La Liga|1995\u201396]]\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[1995\u201396 Copa del Rey|1995\u201396]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Don Bal\u00f3n Award]]: Best Coach 1995-96<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/spanpoy.html|title=Don Bal\u00f3n Awards - RSSSF}}</ref>\n*[[Serbian_Footballer_of_the_Year#Coach_of_the_Year|Serbian Coach of the year]]: 2009\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Radomir Anti\u0107}}\n* {{Reprezentacija|antic-radomir}}\n* {{BDFutbol manager|5092}}\n\n{{Serbia squad 2010 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = Gold\n| fg = Black\n| bordercolor = Black\n| list1 =\n{{La Liga Coach of the Year}}\n{{Football Association of Serbia Coach of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{Real Zaragoza managers}}\n{{Real Madrid CF managers}}\n{{Real Oviedo managers}}\n{{Atl\u00e9tico Madrid managers}}\n{{FC Barcelona managers}}\n{{Celta de Vigo managers}}\n{{Serbia national football team managers}}\n{{Shandong Luneng Taishan F.C. managers}}\n{{Hebei China Fortune F.C. managers}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Antic, Radomir}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Serbian people of Bosnia and Herzegovina descent]]\n[[Category:People from \u017diti\u0161te]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav footballers]]\n[[Category:Serbian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:FK Sloboda U\u017eice players]]\n[[Category:FK Partizan players]]\n[[Category:Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza players]]\n[[Category:Luton Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League players]]\n[[Category:S\u00fcper Lig players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslavia international footballers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav football managers]]\n[[Category:Serbian football managers]]\n[[Category:FK Partizan non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza managers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF managers]]\n[[Category:Real Oviedo managers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid managers]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona managers]]\n[[Category:RC Celta de Vigo managers]]\n[[Category:Serbia national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Shandong Luneng Taishan F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Hebei China Fortune F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Chinese Super League managers]]\n[[Category:China League One managers]]\n[[Category:2010 FIFA World Cup managers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Serbia and Montenegro expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Serbia and Montenegro expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in China]]\n[[Category:Serbian emigrants to Spain]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of Spain]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c5:9519:300:101:2977:48d1:8180", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radomir_Anti%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "History of the Jews in Hong Kong", "text_new": "{{Use Hong Kong English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group     = Jews in Hong Kong<br>{{Hebrew|\u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2 \u05e7\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2}}\n|pop       = about '''2,500'''<ref>[http://www.worldjewishcongress.org/en/about/communities/HK Community in Hong Kong :: World Jewish Congress]</ref>\n|region1   = {{flag|Hong Kong SAR}}\n|pop1      = about '''2,500'''\n|languages = [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], English, [[French language|French]], [[Cantonese]]\n|religions = [[Judaism]]\n|related   = Other [[Jew]]ish groups<br />{{smaller|([[Mizrahi Jews|Mizrahi]], [[Ashkenazi Jews|Ashkenazi]], [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardi]], etc.)}}\n}}\n{{Ethnic Hong Kong sidebar}}\n{{Demographics and Culture of Hong Kong}}\n\n[[Jews]] have been present in [[Hong Kong]] since the mid-19th century. As a major [[financial centre]], much of Hong Kong's Jewish community is temporary in nature, largely consisting of [[expatriate]]s from countries with much larger Jewish populations, such as [[Israel]], [[United States]], [[France]], and other countries.\n\n==History==\n===1800s-1960s: origins===\nJews first arrived in Hong Kong when the territory was ceded to [[Great Britain]] by China in 1842. The Jews transferred their offices from neighboring [[Guangzhou|Canton]] and [[Portuguese Macau|Macau]] (a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] settlement) to Hong Kong and helped to develop this new port.\n\nThe Hong Kong Jewish Community was first established in 1857. The first synagogue was set up in a rental house on Hollywood Street in 1870. A new synagogue in memory of Sir [[Jacob Sassoon]]'s mother, Leah, replaced the older one in 1881. The [[Ohel Leah Synagogue]] was constructed in 1901, the communal cemetery was enlarged in 1904 to meet the needs of the community with assistance of Sir [[Matthew Nathan]], the only Jewish governor of Hong Kong, and the Jewish Club, built by the [[Kadoorie family]], was created in 1904 and enlarged in 1909.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7QEjPVyd9YMC&pg=PA517 Encyclopedia of Diasporas. Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World. Vol. I, Jewish Diaspora in China by Xu Xin, p.162, Ember, Melvin; Ember, Carol R.; Skoggard, Ian (Eds.), Springer 2004] {{ISBN|0-306-48321-1}}</ref> \n\nThe Jewish population, which had totaled 60 Sephardim in 1882, grew to 100 in 1921 (mostly Sephardim), and 250 in 1954 (half Sephardim and half Ashkenazim). Growth then slowed, and the population numbered only 230 in 1959, and 200 in 1968 (70 Sephardim and 130 Ashkenazim).<ref>[https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/hongkong.html The Virtual Jewish History Tour - Hong Kong]</ref> [[Ho Fook]] and [[Robert Hotung]]'s father was the [[History of Jews in the Netherlands|Jewish Dutch]] man Charles Henri Maurice Bosman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.clement-jones.com/ps02/ps02_340.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822055907/http://www.clement-jones.com/ps02/ps02_340.htm |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Jewish community did not grow quickly, as most Jewish merchants were attracted to Shanghai, especially in the period from 1910 to 1936. However, the [[Japanese occupation of China|Japanese occupation of mainland China]] in the late 1930s caused many Jews to leave [[Shanghai]], [[Tianjin]], and [[Harbin]] for Hong Kong.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7QEjPVyd9YMC&pg=PA517 Encyclopedia of Diasporas. Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World. Vol. I, Jewish Diaspora in China by Xu Xin, pp.162-163, Ember, Melvin; Ember, Carol R.; Skoggard, Ian (Eds.), Springer 2004] {{ISBN|0-306-48321-1}}</ref> The outbreak of [[World War II]] and the consequent [[Japanese occupation of Hong Kong]] temporarily suspended all Jewish activities there.\n\n===1960s-1990s: expansion===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2014}}\nFrom the 1960s onwards, Hong Kong's development as a [[trade]] and [[finance]] centre attracted tens of thousands of foreigners, among them Jews from the United States, Israel, the UK, Australia and Canada. They revitalized the local Jewish community. Since the 1960s, Israel also began to appoint Honorary Consuls to Hong Kong.\n\n===Present day===\nThere were 2,500 Jews living in Hong Kong (two thirds of them Americans and Israelis) according to the statistics of the Israeli embassy as of February 1998, up from 1000 around the 1980s.<ref>M.Ejlenberg</ref> It is estimated that about 5,000 Jews lived in Hong Kong in 2000,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7QEjPVyd9YMC&pg=PA517 Encyclopedia of Diasporas. Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World. Vol. I, Jewish Diaspora in China by Xu Xin, p.163, Ember, Melvin; Ember, Carol R.; Skoggard, Ian (Eds.), Springer 2004] {{ISBN|0-306-48321-1}}</ref> and 6,000 in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oakton.edu/user/~friend/trip_stern.html |title=Jews in China |access-date=12 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091019061343/http://www.oakton.edu/user/~friend/trip_stern.html |archive-date=19 October 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThere are now four congregations (the Orthodox Ohel Leah Congregation, the [[Chabad|Chabad-Lubavitch]] Congregation, the Progressive United Jewish Congregation, and the Conservative Shuva Israel Congregation), which have their own [[rabbis]] and places of worship.<ref>[http://www.haruth.com/AsianHongKong.html Jews of Hong Kong]</ref> There is also a large [[Jewish Community Centre]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jcc.org.hk/links.htm |title=Jewish Community Centre, Hong Kong |access-date=12 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522083733/http://www.jcc.org.hk/links.htm |archive-date=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> library, recreational facilities and a [[kosher]] restaurant, and is the leading venue of Jewish activities in the city. There are two Jewish schools, the Carmel school, providing a nursery school program and grades K-12, and the Ezekiel Abraham school which provides after school learning for older children.\n\n==Synagogues==\n[[File:Ohel leah hk.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Ohel Leah Synagogue]]\n[[File:Shuva israel hk.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Shuva Israel Synagogue (the windows with green curtains on the third floor of the building in the center)]]\n===Ohel Leah Synagogue===\nThe [[Ohel Leah Synagogue]] ({{lang-he-n|\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d4\u05db\u05e0\u05e1\u05ea \u05d0\u05d4\u05dc \u05dc\u05d0\u05d4}}) was first founded by Jacob Sasson and his brother on [[Hollywood Road]] in 1870, and moved from place to place over the years. In 1899 they agreed that a new and permanent synagogue should be built, to search for the right field, Emmanuel Raphael, a successful Jewish merchant who was also a member of the board of the [[The Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation|Hong Kong-Shanghai Bank]] found a place he thought was suitable for the construction of the new synagogue on Kennedy Street. Despite this, the synagogue was not built there because it was not possible to collect enough money to buy the land, and also because of differences of opinion with the rest of the community regarding how much of the land would be devoted to the construction of the synagogue. Finally, it was decided to build a synagogue on [[Robinson Road, Hong Kong|Robinson Road]] at a cost of $26,000, paid by the [[Sassoon family]]. The cornerstone was laid by Avraham Haim Yaakov Rahamim and Sasson & Co. on 7 August 1901. The synagogue called \"Ohel Leah\" Memory mother of founder Yakov Eliyahu David Sassoon, who died in May 1878. Construction of the synagogue was completed in 1902.<ref name=\"ohel\">{{cite book |title=[[:he:\u05e4\u05e2\u05de\u05d9\u05dd]] |pages=98-99}}</ref><ref name=\"jhk\">{{cite book |title=\u05e1\u05ea\u05d9\u05d5-\u05d7\u05d5\u05e8\u05e3 \u05ea\u05e9\u05e1\"\u05d5 |pages=333-350}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1980s, the synagogue's board of governors discussed the possibility of demolishing the synagogue and building it elsewhere. The land on which the synagogue was built cost much more than the price at which it was purchased, and it seemed to them that it would be better to sell the land and to receive a new synagogue. The idea of demolishing the synagogue was dropped after one of the women who was present insisted that a synagogue should not be destroyed. However, the idea of selling the land did not come out of the chapter, and the land was finally sold, but only in half. The synagogue area remained intact, the synagogue was renovated, and the second area was built with two very tall residential buildings known as Robinson one. The lower five floors are owned by the Jewish community, including a kosher restaurant, pool, library and other community needs.<ref name=\"ohel\"/>\n\nThe synagogue was built by Iraqi merchants, over the years, however, the synagogue underwent many vicissitudes, and today the style of the prayer is Sephardic with an Israeli accent. Almost all prayers are held in the synagogue, except for [[Mincha]] and Arabic prayers on weekdays (not including Sundays and holidays).<ref name=\"ohel\"/>\n\n===Shuva Israel===\n \nThe Shuva Israel community ({{lang-he-n|\u05e7\u05d4\u05d9\u05dc\u05ea \u05e9\u05d5\u05d1\u05d4 \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc}}) located on the Connaught road in [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]] was established in October 1991 by the Darwish family following differences of opinion between David Darwish, then head of the Jewish Community Department, and other Jewish officials in Hong Kong. \"Shuva Israel\" was intended for a more ultra-Orthodox public.<ref name=\"jhk\"/>\n\nThe first rabbi of the community was Rabbi David Avraham. The community also operates kollel students and a kosher restaurant. The community had an ultra-Orthodox school, which was closed in 2006, when the founding family moved to Israel.<ref name=\"jhk\"/>\n\n===Chabad Hong Kong and Kowloon===\n\nThe [[Chabad]] of Hong Kong was established in the 1980s by Rabbi Mordechai Avtzon and his wife Goldie. Chabad House Hong Kong was the first in the [[Far East]]. In addition, he founded the \"Lubavitch of the Far East\" (LIFE Lubavitch of the Far East). In 2009, another Chabad house was established in the [[Kowloon Peninsula]], led by Rabbi Yisrael Liberman.\n\n===Kehilat Zion===\n\nKehilat Zion ({{lang-he-n|\u05e7\u05d4\u05d9\u05dc\u05ea \u05e6\u05d9\u05d5\u05df}}) located in [[Kowloon]] was established in 1995 by Rabbi Shlomo Katsin. At first Rabbi Zion Mizrachi was sent to serve as rabbi of the community, named after him. The community is mainly used by local businessmen and those who are invited to visit their businesses. Rabbi Meoded serves as the chief rabbi of the Sephardic community in Hong Kong and also serves as the Chief Rabbi of Hong Kong, where there is a synagogue and a kosher restaurant serving kosher food and Shabbat meals.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Judaism]]\n*[[Japanese occupation of Hong Kong]]\n*[[History of the Jews in China]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.jcc.org.hk/ Jewish community center (JCC) in Hong Kong website]\n* [http://www.ohelleah.org/ Ohel Leah Synagogue website]\n* [http://www.shuva-israel.com/ Shuva Israel community website] (in Hebrew)\n* [http://www.chabadhongkong.org/ Chabad Hong Kong website]\n* [http://kehilat-zion.org/index_he.php Kiryat Zion website] (in Hebrew)\n* [https://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4269702,00.html \u05e2\u05d5\u05d3 \u05d1\u05d4\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2 \u05e7\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2 \u2013 \u05d4\u05e0\u05e7\u05d5\u05d3\u05d4 \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9\u05ea (more in Hong Kong - the Jews)], 2012 (in Hebrew)\n* [http://jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI_Heb/SharedView.Article.aspx?parm=lY2hYO6P6VPo3g%2BftVJ%2FNKUEvlQuu4s4wx7yHMeE2z%2FHdTbTtpNAZ68czjvVd94fYw%3D%3D&mode=image&href=HZF%2f1888%2f01%2f10&page=1&rtl=true \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d4\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2 \u05e7\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2 \u05d5\u05d1\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5 \u05d4\u05e1\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd (Jews in Hong Kong and China)], 1888 (in Hebrew)\n*[https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/hong-kong The Jewish Community of Hong Kong - The Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot]\n*[http://www.urbanphoto.net/blog/2010/12/09/judaism-with-a-hong-kong-flavour/ Judaism With a Hong Kong Flavour] at Urbanphoto.net\n\n{{Asia in topic|History of the Jews in}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Hong Kong|Jews]]\n[[Category:History of Hong Kong|Jewish]]\n[[Category:Jewish history by city|Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Jewish Hong Kong history| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Hong Kong English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group     = Jews in Hong Kong<br>{{Hebrew|\u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2 \u05e7\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2}}\n|pop       = about '''2,500'''<ref>[http://www.worldjewishcongress.org/en/about/communities/HK Community in Hong Kong :: World Jewish Congress]</ref>\n|region1   = {{flag|Hong Kong SAR}}\n|pop1      = about '''2,500'''\n|languages = [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], English, [[French language|French]], [[Cantonese]]\n|religions = [[Judaism]]\n|related   = Other [[Jew]]ish groups<br />{{smaller|([[Mizrahi Jews|Mizrahi]], [[Ashkenazi Jews|Ashkenazi]], [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardi]], etc.)}}\n}}\n{{Ethnic Hong Kong sidebar}}\n{{Demographics and Culture of Hong Kong}}\n\n[[Jews]] have been present in [[Hong Kong]] since the mid-19th century. As a major [[financial centre]], much of Hong Kong's Jewish community is temporary in nature, largely consisting of [[expatriate]]s from countries with much larger Jewish populations, such as [[Israel]], [[United States]], [[France]], and other countries.\n\n==History==\n===1800s-1960s: origins===\nJews first arrived in Hong Kong when the territory was ceded to [[Great Britain]] by China in 1842. The Jews transferred their offices from neighboring [[Guangzhou|Canton]] and [[Portuguese Macau|Macau]] (a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] settlement) to Hong Kong and helped to develop this new port.\n\nThe Hong Kong Jewish Community was first established in 1857. The first synagogue was set up in a rental house on Hollywood Street in 1870. A new synagogue in memory of Sir [[Jacob Sassoon]]'s mother, Leah, replaced the older one in 1881. The [[Ohel Leah Synagogue]] was constructed in 1901, the communal cemetery was enlarged in 1904 to meet the needs of the community with assistance of Sir [[Matthew Nathan]], the only Jewish governor of Hong Kong, and the Jewish Club, built by the [[Kadoorie family]], was created in 1904 and enlarged in 1909.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7QEjPVyd9YMC&pg=PA517 Encyclopedia of Diasporas. Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World. Vol. I, Jewish Diaspora in China by Xu Xin, p.162, Ember, Melvin; Ember, Carol R.; Skoggard, Ian (Eds.), Springer 2004] {{ISBN|0-306-48321-1}}</ref> \n\nThe Jewish population, which had totaled 60 Sephardim in 1882, grew to 100 in 1921 (mostly Sephardim), and 250 in 1954 (half Sephardim and half Ashkenazim). Growth then slowed, and the population numbered only 230 in 1959, and 200 in 1968 (70 Sephardim and 130 Ashkenazim).<ref>[https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/hongkong.html The Virtual Jewish History Tour - Hong Kong]</ref> [[Ho Fook]] and [[Robert Hotung]]'s father was the [[History of Jews in the Netherlands|Jewish Dutch]] man Charles Henri Maurice Bosman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.clement-jones.com/ps02/ps02_340.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822055907/http://www.clement-jones.com/ps02/ps02_340.htm |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Jewish community did not grow quickly, as most Jewish merchants were attracted to Shanghai, especially in the period from 1910 to 1936. However, the [[Japanese occupation of China|Japanese occupation of mainland China]] in the late 1930s caused many Jews to leave [[Shanghai]], [[Tianjin]], and [[Harbin]] for Hong Kong.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7QEjPVyd9YMC&pg=PA517 Encyclopedia of Diasporas. Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World. Vol. I, Jewish Diaspora in China by Xu Xin, pp.162-163, Ember, Melvin; Ember, Carol R.; Skoggard, Ian (Eds.), Springer 2004] {{ISBN|0-306-48321-1}}</ref> The outbreak of [[World War II]] and the consequent [[Japanese occupation of Hong Kong]] temporarily suspended all Jewish activities there.\n\n===1960s-1990s: expansion===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2014}}\nFrom the 1960s onwards, Hong Kong's development as a [[trade]] and [[finance]] centre attracted tens of thousands of foreigners, among them Jews from the United States, Israel, the UK, Australia and Canada. They revitalized the local Jewish community. Since the 1960s, Israel also began to appoint Honorary Consuls to Hong Kong.\n\n===Present day===\nThere were 2,500 Jews living in Hong Kong (two thirds of them Americans and Israelis) according to the statistics of the Israeli embassy as of February 1998, up from 1000 around the 1980s.<ref>M.Ejlenberg</ref> It is estimated that about 5,000 Jews lived in Hong Kong in 2000,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7QEjPVyd9YMC&pg=PA517 Encyclopedia of Diasporas. Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World. Vol. I, Jewish Diaspora in China by Xu Xin, p.163, Ember, Melvin; Ember, Carol R.; Skoggard, Ian (Eds.), Springer 2004] {{ISBN|0-306-48321-1}}</ref> and 6,000 in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oakton.edu/user/~friend/trip_stern.html |title=Jews in China |access-date=12 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091019061343/http://www.oakton.edu/user/~friend/trip_stern.html |archive-date=19 October 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThere are now four congregations (the Orthodox Ohel Leah Congregation, the [[Chabad|Chabad-Lubavitch]] Congregation, the Progressive United Jewish Congregation, and the Conservative Shuva Israel Congregation), which have their own [[rabbis]] and places of worship.<ref>[http://www.haruth.com/AsianHongKong.html Jews of Hong Kong]</ref> There is also a large [[Jewish Community Centre]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jcc.org.hk/links.htm |title=Jewish Community Centre, Hong Kong |access-date=12 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522083733/http://www.jcc.org.hk/links.htm |archive-date=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> library, recreational facilities and a [[kosher]] restaurant, and is the leading venue of Jewish activities in the city. There are two Jewish schools, the Carmel school, providing a nursery school program and grades K-12, and the Ezekiel Abraham school which provides after school learning for older children.\n\n==Synagogues==\n[[File:Ohel leah hk.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Ohel Leah Synagogue]]\n[[File:Shuva israel hk.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Shuva Israel Synagogue (the windows with green curtains on the third floor of the building in the center)]]\n===Ohel Leah Synagogue===\nThe [[Ohel Leah Synagogue]] ({{lang-he-n|\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d4\u05db\u05e0\u05e1\u05ea \u05d0\u05d4\u05dc \u05dc\u05d0\u05d4}}) was first founded by Jacob Sasson and his brother on [[Hollywood Road]] in 1870 , and moved from place to place over the years. In 1899 they agreed that a new and permanent synagogue should be built, to search for the right field, Emmanuel Raphael, a successful Jewish merchant who was also a member of the board of the [[The Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation|Hong Kong-Shanghai Bank]] found a place he thought was suitable for the construction of the new synagogue on Kennedy Street. Despite this, the synagogue was not built there because it was not possible to collect enough money to buy the land, and also because of differences of opinion with the rest of the community regarding how much of the land would be devoted to the construction of the synagogue. Finally, it was decided to build a synagogue on [[Robinson Road, Hong Kong|Robinson Road]] at a cost of $26,000, paid by the [[Sassoon family]]. The cornerstone was laid by Avraham Haim Yaakov Rahamim and Sasson & Co. on 7 August 1901. The synagogue called \"Ohel Leah\" Memory mother of founder Yakov Eliyahu David Sassoon, who died in May 1878. Construction of the synagogue was completed in 1902.<ref name=\"ohel\">{{cite book |title=[[:he:\u05e4\u05e2\u05de\u05d9\u05dd]] |pages=98-99}}</ref><ref name=\"jhk\">{{cite book |title=\u05e1\u05ea\u05d9\u05d5-\u05d7\u05d5\u05e8\u05e3 \u05ea\u05e9\u05e1\"\u05d5 |pages=333-350}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1980s, the synagogue's board of governors discussed the possibility of demolishing the synagogue and building it elsewhere. The land on which the synagogue was built cost much more than the price at which it was purchased, and it seemed to them that it would be better to sell the land and to receive a new synagogue. The idea of demolishing the synagogue was dropped after one of the women who was present insisted that a synagogue should not be destroyed. However, the idea of selling the land did not come out of the chapter, and the land was finally sold, but only in half. The synagogue area remained intact, the synagogue was renovated, and the second area was built with two very tall residential buildings known as Robinson one. The lower five floors are owned by the Jewish community, including a kosher restaurant, pool, library and other community needs.<ref name=\"ohel\"/>\n\nThe synagogue was built by Iraqi merchants, over the years, however, the synagogue underwent many vicissitudes, and today the style of the prayer is Sephardic with an Israeli accent. Almost all prayers are held in the synagogue, except for [[Mincha]] and Arabic prayers on weekdays (not including Sundays and holidays).<ref name=\"ohel\"/>\n\n===Shuva Israel===\n \nThe Shuva Israel community ({{lang-he-n|\u05e7\u05d4\u05d9\u05dc\u05ea \u05e9\u05d5\u05d1\u05d4 \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc}}) located on the Connaught road in [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]] was established in October 1991 by the Darwish family following differences of opinion between David Darwish, then head of the Jewish Community Department, and other Jewish officials in Hong Kong. \"Shuva Israel\" was intended for a more ultra-Orthodox public.<ref name=\"jhk\"/>\n\nThe first rabbi of the community was Rabbi David Avraham. The community also operates kollel students and a kosher restaurant. The community had an ultra-Orthodox school, which was closed in 2006, when the founding family moved to Israel.<ref name=\"jhk\"/>\n\n===Chabad Hong Kong and Kowloon===\n\nThe [[Chabad]] of Hong Kong was established in the 1980s by Rabbi Mordechai Avtzon and his wife Goldie. Chabad House Hong Kong was the first in the [[Far East]]. In addition, he founded the \"Lubavitch of the Far East\" (LIFE Lubavitch of the Far East). In 2009, another Chabad house was established in the [[Kowloon Peninsula]], led by Rabbi Yisrael Liberman.\n\n===Kehilat Zion===\n\nKehilat Zion ({{lang-he-n|\u05e7\u05d4\u05d9\u05dc\u05ea \u05e6\u05d9\u05d5\u05df}}) located in [[Kowloon]] was established in 1995 by Rabbi Shlomo Katsin. At first Rabbi Zion Mizrachi was sent to serve as rabbi of the community, named after him. The community is mainly used by local businessmen and those who are invited to visit their businesses. Rabbi Meoded serves as the chief rabbi of the Sephardic community in Hong Kong and also serves as the Chief Rabbi of Hong Kong, where there is a synagogue and a kosher restaurant serving kosher food and Shabbat meals.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Judaism]]\n*[[Japanese occupation of Hong Kong]]\n*[[History of the Jews in China]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.jcc.org.hk/ Jewish community center (JCC) in Hong Kong website]\n* [http://www.ohelleah.org/ Ohel Leah Synagogue website]\n* [http://www.shuva-israel.com/ Shuva Israel community website] (in Hebrew)\n* [http://www.chabadhongkong.org/ Chabad Hong Kong website]\n* [http://kehilat-zion.org/index_he.php Kiryat Zion website] (in Hebrew)\n* [https://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4269702,00.html \u05e2\u05d5\u05d3 \u05d1\u05d4\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2 \u05e7\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2 \u2013 \u05d4\u05e0\u05e7\u05d5\u05d3\u05d4 \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9\u05ea (more in Hong Kong - the Jews)], 2012 (in Hebrew)\n* [http://jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI_Heb/SharedView.Article.aspx?parm=lY2hYO6P6VPo3g%2BftVJ%2FNKUEvlQuu4s4wx7yHMeE2z%2FHdTbTtpNAZ68czjvVd94fYw%3D%3D&mode=image&href=HZF%2f1888%2f01%2f10&page=1&rtl=true \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d4\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2 \u05e7\u05d5\u05e0\u05d2 \u05d5\u05d1\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5 \u05d4\u05e1\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd (Jews in Hong Kong and China)], 1888 (in Hebrew)\n*[https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/hong-kong The Jewish Community of Hong Kong - The Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot]\n*[http://www.urbanphoto.net/blog/2010/12/09/judaism-with-a-hong-kong-flavour/ Judaism With a Hong Kong Flavour] at Urbanphoto.net\n\n{{Asia in topic|History of the Jews in}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Hong Kong|Jews]]\n[[Category:History of Hong Kong|Jewish]]\n[[Category:Jewish history by city|Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Jewish Hong Kong history| ]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOhel Leah Synagogue:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: ,  \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Jews_in_Hong_Kong"}
{"title_page": "1905\u201306 British Home Championship", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox international football competition\n|tourney_name=1905\u20131906 British Home Championship\n|image      =\n|size       =\n|caption    =\n|country    =England, Ireland, Scotland and Wales\n|dates      =17 February\u20137 April 1906\n|num_teams  =4\n|champion_other=Shared: {{fb|ENG}}/{{fb|SCO}}\n|attendance =\n|matches    =6\n|goals      =20\n|top_scorer ={{fbicon|WAL|1807}} [[William Green (footballer)|William Green]] and {{fbicon|IRE}} [[Harold Sloan]] {{nowrap|(3 goals)}}\n|prevseason =[[1901\u201302 British Home Championship|1901\u20131902]]\n|nextseason =[[1903\u201304 British Home Championship|1903\u201304]]\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\nThe '''1905\u201306 [[British Home Championship]]''' was the 22nd edition of the annual international [[football (soccer)|football]] tournament played between the British [[Home Nations]]. The trophy was shared between the two sides which regularly dominated the competition, [[England national football team|England]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] who each gained four points.\n\nEngland and [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] began the tournament in February 1906, with England scoring five goals without reply and rising to the head of the table. [[Wales national football team|Wales]] joined them after their match with Scotland which they won in [[Edinburgh]] 2\u20130. Scotland recovered to beat Ireland by a single goal and England then moved ahead by beating Wales with an identical scoreline. Playing for lower rankings, Wales and Ireland fought out a thrilling 4\u20134 draw in [[Cardiff]] before the deciding game between England and Scotland. England needed only a draw to take the trophy undisputed, but Scotland played well and in flowing match triumphed 2\u20131 to share the honours.\n\nParts of the Wales vs Ireland match at Wrexham were filmed by the Blackburn company of Mitchell and Kenyon, and is now the oldest surviving footage of an international football match.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=John |editor1-last=Davies|editor1-link=John Davies (historian)|editor2-first=Nigel |editor2-last=Jenkins | editor2-link=Nigel Jenkins| editor3-first=Baines |editor3-last=Menna|editor4-first=Peredur I. |editor4-last=Lynch|title=The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |year=2008 |publisher=University of Wales Press |location=Cardiff|page=282 |isbn=978-0-7083-1953-6}}</ref>\n\n==Table==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|show_positions=n\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=ENG|name_ENG={{fb|ENG}}\n|team2=SCO|name_SCO={{fb|SCO}}\n|team3=WAL|name_WAL={{fb|WAL|1807}}\n|team4=IRE|name_IRE={{fb|IRE}}\n|win_ENG=2|draw_ENG=0|loss_ENG=1|gf_ENG=7|ga_ENG=2|status_ENG=C\n|win_SCO=2|draw_SCO=0|loss_SCO=1|gf_SCO=3|ga_SCO=3|status_SCO=C\n|win_WAL=1|draw_WAL=1|loss_WAL=1|gf_WAL=6|ga_WAL=5\n|win_IRE=0|draw_IRE=1|loss_IRE=2|gf_IRE=4|ga_IRE=10\n|status_text_C=Co-champions\n|col_C=#ccffcc|text_C=\n|result1=C|result2=C\n|update=complete|source=\n|class_rules = 1) points. The points system worked as follows: 2 points for a win and 1 point for a draw.\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Results==\n{{football box \n | date = 17 February 1906\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|IRE}}\n | score = 0 \u2013 5\n | team2 = {{fb|ENG}}\n | goals1 = &nbsp; \n | goals2 = {{goal|26||89|}} [[Dicky Bond]] <br />{{goal|32}} [[Arthur Brown (footballer, born 1885)|Arthur Brown]] <br />{{goal|56}} [[Stanley Harris (footballer)|Stanley Harris]] <br />{{goal|70}} [[Samuel Day (sportsman)|Samuel Day]]\n | stadium = [[Solitude (football ground)|Solitude]], [[Belfast]] \n | attendance = 14,063\n | referee = Tom Robertson ([[Scottish Football Association|Scotland]])\n}}\n----\n{{football box \n | date = 3 March 1906\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|SCO}}\n | score = 0 \u2013 2\n | team2 = {{fb|WAL|1807}}\n | goals1 = &nbsp; \n | goals2 = {{goal|50}} [[Lot Jones]]<br />{{goal|65}} [[John Love Jones]]\n | stadium =